    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Pride of New York</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sarena Barnett and Amorit Barnett letter on July 12 article says they make no effort to fit in when they visit other United States cities so that they can boast of being New Yorkers when asked where they come from</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In the City of Lights or in the City of Angels, How to Go Local'' (Vacation section, July 12):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In the City of Lights or in the City of Angels, How to Go Local'' (Vacation section, July 12):</p>
        <p>Although we found the tips offered by your correspondents on how to avoid looking like an out-of-towner amusing, we believe them to be wholly unnecessary.</p>
        <p>As sisters who love to travel in the United States, we are never ashamed to look like the tourists we often mock on the streets of our native New York City.</p>
        <p>In fact, we are thrilled to be identified as tourists because we expect the inevitable question, ''Where are you guys from?''</p>
        <p>That is our cue to answer gleefully, ''New York City!''</p>
        <p>Yo, when you're from the greatest city in the world, you don't want to hide it.</p>
        <p>SARENA BARNETT  AMORIT BARNETT  Kew Gardens, Queens, July 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
